GENERAL:

In accordance with 40 CFR Part 68.155, this executive summary includes a brief description of the following program elements:

The accidental release prevention and emergency response policies at the Ferro facility;
The Ferro facility and regulated substances handled;
The worst case release scenario;
The general accidental release prevention program and chemical specific steps;
The five year accident history;
The emergency response program; and
Planned changes to improve safety.

It should be noted that TiCl4 is the only regulated substance that is present in a process over threshold quantities. HCl has been included in the RMP under the General Duty clause because it is generated when TiCl4 reacts with water.

ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE POLICIES:

The Ferro facility maintains this RMP in accordance with Section 112(r) of the CAA in addition to a Spill Prevention Report in accordance with New York State?s Chemical Bulk Storage (CBS) regulations (6 NYCRR Parts 595-599). Both of these documents include accidental release prevention provisions for the TiCl4 process at the facility. Additionally, the Ferro facility maintains a Hazardous Waste Contingency Plan which includes provisions for emergency response in the event of an accidental release of TiCl4.

FERRO FACILITY AND REGULATED SUBSTANCES:

The Ferro facility stores up to 5,000 gallons (72,350 pounds) of liquid TiCl4 in one 5,000 gallon aboveground storage tank, which exceeds the threshold quantity of 2,500 pounds specified in the 112(r) rule. The TiCl4 is used to provide titanium for the ceramic manufacturing process. In accordance with the CAA General Duty clause, Ferro has identified an additional potential for exposure due to the reactive nature of TiCl4 with water. Ferro is upgrading its program level from Program 1 to Program 2 to account for the potential generation of HCl gas from a TiCl4 release. HCl is not a chemical used by Ferro in a regulated process, but is strictl
